				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Beasties that summon<a name="6095"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Apr 9 03 10:57 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Summoning sucks when soloing that is for sure.  Basically there is no way to tell if a mob summons before you start kiting it.  There are a capable of strong indicators though.  First of all, in order to summon, the mob has to be level 51+ as you mentioned.  There are like two mobs in the entire game that don't meet that requirement (anyone ever been summoned by Tailfang in the crater around Shar Vahl, now that is embarrassing).  Anyway, the trick after that is to figure out which 51+ mobs summon.  Here are some general rules.  If the mob is in Kunark, it probably summons, heck it almost definetly summons.  Kunark is the expansion known for summoning mobs and it is full of them.  If its a named mob, it also probably summons, there are exceptions to this rule though.  I have noticed that casting mobs have a better chance of summoning than non-casting mobs.  This does not mean that warrior and monk class mobs cannot summon, if you don't believe me try kiting Veltar in DL sometime.  In the Planes of Power, most mobs do not summon.  Best thing to do with these ones is just try them and if you get summoned try to escape and don't fight them again.  There are also threads on Concert Hall and EQ Diva that deal with summoning mobs in the planes.  This pretty much somes up summoning mobs, though I would like to add one last thing.  Mobs do not start summoning until they are at about 95% health.  This allows you to kite one around for a bit safely if you need to for some reason (Gorenaire and Talendor are two examples that come to mind), and can also trick you into thinking you have found a non-summoning mob when you really haven't.  Anyway, good luck and have fun.
<br />
</span></td>
